civil war is about more than
just Assad, the

22:20.773 --> 22:25.878 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Islamic State, and American
interests in the
region. It's about millions of
real families

22:25.911 --> 22:28.948 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
left with nowhere to turn who
are looking
for a better future.

22:28.981 --> 22:33.552 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANNE BARNARD: This story reminds
us that each
one of these stories is an
individual tale

22:33.586 --> 22:40.859 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and each -- even this one
family. That incredibly
tragic picture of Alan on the
beach was only

22:40.893 --> 22:43.229 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a tiny piece of what they had
been through.

22:43.262 --> 22:45.998 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What happened to Alan was just a
fraction
of what happened to them. And
what happened

22:46.031 --> 22:51.036 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to them is just one story out of
many millions
of stories. Half of the Syrian
population

22:51.070 --> 22:54.807 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has been displaced in this
conflict. So I
think we just have to remember
that each one

22:54.840 --> 22:59.311 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of these stories is a real
person with a real
family, with family dynamics
like those we

22:59.345 --> 23:00.679 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
have in our own families.

23:00.713 --> 23:03.549 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: And for Tima
Kurdi, the
story is far from over.

23:03.582 --> 23:11.657 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FATIMA KURDI: Of course, the sad
part, you
always think about the rest of
the family,

23:11.690 --> 23:17.796 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
about a million of those
refugees. They are
still -- have a little bit of
hope one day

23:17.830 --> 23:19.665 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
they will be somewhere safe.

23:19.698 --> 23:24.103 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: After her
nephew's tragic
death, Tima has become an
outspoken activist

23:24.136 --> 23:26.705 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and advocate for the plight of
refugees around
the world.

23:26.739 --> 23:34.313 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FATIMA KURDI: People have to
open their heart
and their door and help them.
And that's why

23:34.346 --> 23:42.888 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I said, if I have a chance to
bring my voice
to the world, I'm willing to do
it. It's not

23:42.921 --> 23:50.329 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
something I choose. I just -- it
happened.
And it's not an easy thing to
do, really.

23:50.362 --> 23:56.068 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: A dire
challenge now faced
by the U.S., European and Middle
Eastern nations

23:56.101 --> 23:57.102 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
alike.

23:57.136 --> 24:00.706 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
William Brangham.

24:00.739 --> 24:12.084 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

24:12.117 --> 24:18.123 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour":
examining why
the Oscar nominees still lack
diversity; the

24:18.157 --> 24:24.263 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
tough job market for women over
50; and what
it takes to make a great
photograph.

24:24.296 --> 24:31.303 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, first, what the White House
is calling
the moon shot to cure cancer.
One unexpected

24:31.337 --> 24:35.574 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
announcement in President
Obama's State of
the Union address came when he
tapped Vice

24:35.607 --> 24:41.580 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Joe Biden to lead an
effort to boost
and streamline cancer research
across the

24:41.613 --> 24:43.449 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
country.

24:43.482 --> 24:46.118 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA, President of the
United States:
Tonight, I'm announcing a new
national effort

24:46.151 --> 24:50.823 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to get it done. And because he's
gone to the
mat for all of us on so many
issues over the

24:50.856 --> 24:53.559 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
past 40 years, I'm putting Joe
in charge of
mission control.

24:53.592 --> 24:55.361 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

24:55.394 --> 25:02.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA: For the loved ones
we've all
lost, for the families that we
can still save,

25:02.935 --> 25:05.771 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
let's make America the country
that cures
cancer once and for all.

25:05.804 --> 25:07.005 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What do you say, Joe?

25:07.039 --> 25:08.874 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

25:08.907 --> 25:12.678 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: For a look at
what an initiative
might look like, and who would
be involved,

25:12.711 --> 25:18.050 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and how it might go forward, we
turn to three
people with long ties to cancer
research.

25:18.083 --> 25:23.822 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Dr. Otis Brawley is chief
medical officer
at the American Cancer Society.
Dr. Francis

25:23.856 --> 25:29.228 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Collins is the director of the
National Institutes
of Health. And Katie Couric, in
addition to

25:29.261 --> 25:33.699 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
being the well-known journalist
and author,
she is also one of the
co-founders of Stand

25:33.732 --> 25:38.404 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Up to Cancer. It's a charitable
group that
supports collaborative research.

25:38.437 --> 25:41.407 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we welcome all three of you
to the program.

25:41.440 --> 25:43.342 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Dr. Brawley, let me start with
you.

25:43.375 --> 25:47.713 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Is it realistic for the
president to say,
let's cure cancer once and for
all?

25:47.746 --> 25:51.750 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. OTIS BRAWLEY, American
Cancer Society:
Well, I think the cure analogy
is fine.

25:51.784 --> 25:57.322 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What's really going to happen is
some cancers,
if we intensify our efforts,
will be cured.

25:57.356 --> 26:02.327 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Many cancers are going to be
stalled out to
where they become very chronic
diseases, like

26:02.361 --> 26:06.832 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
diabetes. But the end result is,
people are
going to be better for it.

26:06.865 --> 26:11.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Francis Collins,
Dr. Collins,
do you agree? I mean, we know
there are, what,

26:11.470 --> 26:17.342 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
over 100 -- maybe hundreds of
types of cancer?
What are people to think about
this?

26:17.376 --> 26:19.578 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. FRANCIS COLLINS, Director,
National Institutes
of Health: Well, I hope they
will be inspired

26:19.611 --> 26:21.346 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and excited about this.

26:21.380 --> 26:25.250 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Yes, there are hundreds of types
of cancer,
but we are at an inflection
point in terms

26:25.284 --> 26:30.489 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of things we are learning about
what causes
this disease, where good cells
go bad, and

26:30.522 --> 26:35.527 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what could we do about it? And
by bring together
immunotherapy, the new way of
activating the

26:35.561 --> 26:40.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
immune system to tackle cancel,
genomics,
and making sure that everybody
is sharing

26:40.599 --> 26:45.304 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the data they're developing in
those kinds
of studies, the vice president,
a man of great

26:45.337 --> 26:50.042 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
passion and principle, is
determined that
this is not going to be a tweak
on the system.

26:50.075 --> 26:55.314 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is going to be a major
acceleration of
the effort to discover how to
treat and cure,

26:55.347 --> 26:59.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in many instances, cancer. And
goodness knows,
we can all get excited about
that outcome.

26:59.585 --> 27:04.056 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Katie
Couric, as somebody
who has been on the advocacy
side of this

27:04.089 --> 27:09.495 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for years, having lost your
first husband
and your sister to cancer, how
do you see

27:09.528 --> 27:11.263 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the challenge?

27:11.296 --> 27:13.699 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATIE COURIC, Stand Up to
Cancer: Well, I
think it's so exciting, Judy,
when I heard

27:13.732 --> 27:19.104 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this announcement at the State
of the Union.
And it's -- I think we are, as
Dr. Collins

27:19.137 --> 27:25.177 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
said, at a really inflection
point, and things
are happening so much when it
comes to immunotherapy,

27:25.210 --> 27:27.980 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as he said, genomics, the basic
science.

27:28.013 --> 27:33.752 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, you know, as somebody who
has lost people
near and dear to my heart, I --
when Vice

27:33.785 --> 27:38.924 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Biden lost Beau, I
literally felt
his pain and frustration. And
that's the way

27:38.957 --> 27:42.828 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I felt when Jay and Emily died.
Why couldn't
there be better treatments?

27:42.861 --> 27:48.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I remember, Judy, the first-line
treatment
for metastatic colon cancer for
Jay in 1999

27:48.166 --> 27:54.773 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- 1997, rather, had been around
since the
1950s. And it just made me
furious. And that

27:54.806 --> 27:56.975 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
was really the impetus for Stand
Up to Cancer.

27:57.009 --> 28:01.380 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We said, you know, these
researchers, these
scientists, they have to
collaborate, instead

28:01.413 --> 28:07.119 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of compete. And we started it in
2008, and
now, eight years later, we have
-- we have

28:07.152 --> 28:14.026 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
1,000 scientists. We have 130
researcher institutions
involved. They're working on 18
different

28:14.059 --> 28:18.497 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
dream teams, where they're
collaborating on
things like pancreatic cancer,
lung cancer

28:18.530 --> 28:21.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
with the American Cancer
Society, childhood
cancers.

28:21.300 --> 28:23.101 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Right.

28:23.135 --> 28:26.939 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATIE COURIC: And it's -- so,
and, already,
two FDA-approved treatments have
stemmed from

28:26.972 --> 28:32.210 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that kind of research for
pancreatic cancer
and lung cancer. So, I think
collaboration

28:32.244 --> 28:33.979 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
really is the key.

28:34.012 --> 28:38.717 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What about that,
Dr. Brawley?
What would constitute a
breakthrough here?

28:38.750 --> 28:45.190 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. OTIS BRAWLEY: Well, I agree
that we need
sustained funding and sustained
support for

28:45.223 --> 28:49.895 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the scientists, especially the
folks at the
National Cancer Institute, who
have been wonderful

28:49.928 --> 28:51.663 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
at this.

28:51.697 --> 28:56.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I do believe that we are at an
inflection
point. We have learned a lot
about what goes

28:56.602 --> 29:02.608 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on in the cancer cell. A lot of
targets that
are druggable are being
developed. We actually

29:02.641 --> 29:09.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
need some command-and-control of
the oncology
research network in order to
advance it further

29:09.414 --> 29:10.482 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and faster.

29:10.515 --> 29:12.317 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What do you mean
command-and-control?

29:12.351 --> 29:18.423 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. OTIS BRAWLEY: Well, we do
need people
to say, this is a project that
needs funding

29:18.457 --> 29:25.263 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and needs funding urgently. This
is a project
that's repetitive and need not
be funded.

29:25.297 --> 29:32.270 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We need people to say, you, as
an investigator,
need to start talking and
collaborating with

29:32.304 --> 29:36.408 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
other investigators. We need to
bring industry
into this.

29:36.441 --> 29:41.480 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We need to bring far more than
just government
and academics. I would also say
the advocacy

29:41.513 --> 29:46.318 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
community needs to be involved.
So, there
needs to be some collaboration
amongst numerous

29:46.351 --> 29:49.521 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
individuals and numerous
organizations.

29:49.554 --> 29:54.960 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But I actually am very
optimistic that we
can do some very positive work
here.

29:54.993 --> 29:59.831 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But, Dr. Collins,
how much
of this is money? We know
something like 265

29:59.865 --> 30:04.503 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
million more dollars went to the
National
Cancer Institute over the last
few years.

30:04.536 --> 30:09.307 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You were responsible for a lot
of that. Is
money the whole story here?

30:09.341 --> 30:13.578 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DR. FRANCIS COLLINS: It's not
the whole story,
but it sure is helpful.

30:13.612 --> 30:18.283 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Investigators who are pursuing
really creative
ideas in cancer research still
have only about

30:18.316 --> 30:22.120 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
one chance in five that their
ideas are going
to get funded, because although
we have now

30:22.154 --> 30:26.058 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
turned the corner -- and much
credit to the
Congress for making that happen
a month ago

30:26.091 --> 30:29.828 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- we still have a long way to
go to catch
up on the resources that we have
lost.

30:29.861 --> 30:35.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if we're really going to
jump-start this
kind of opportunity for moving
cancer research

30:35.233 --> 30:39.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
forward at an accelerated pace,
resources
are going to be critical. We are
not lacking

30:39.538 --> 30:44.376 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for ideas. We're not lacking for
talent. There
are all kinds of things
happening in this

30:44.409 --> 30:46.178 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
field.

30:46.211 --> 30:48.947 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Resources are really critical to
make it possible
to move forward at the rate that
I know we

30:48.980 --> 30:54.419 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
could. Take immunotherapy. We
have seen how
the immune system, probably in
all of us,

30:54.453 --> 30:59.091 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is searching out and taking care
of small
numbers of cancer cells every
day, and we

30:59.124 --> 31:00.892 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
never even know we had them.

31:00.926 --> 31:05.697 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, sometimes, the cancer cells
are clever
enough to elude that. We have
seen dramatic

31:05.731 --> 31:10.202 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
results in melanoma, President
Carter with
his metastatic melanoma. Now,
apparently,

31:10.235 --> 31:10.802 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
those brain...

31:10.836 --> 31:11.369 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

31:11.403 --> 31:12.237 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stunning.

31:12.270 --> 31:14.005 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DR. FRANCIS COLLINS: ... melted
away.

31:14.039 --> 31:18.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we need to move that into
other areas,
like pancreatic cancer, like
lung cancer,

31:18.543 --> 31:22.781 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
breast cancer, prostate cancer,
where the
immune system is having an even
harder time

31:22.814 --> 31:24.616 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
finding what is there.

31:24.649 --> 31:29.755 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But those cancers have abnormal
proteins.
They should be approachable. We
need to teach

31:29.788 --> 31:34.226 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the immune system, take it to
college, take
it to graduate school, figure
out how we can

31:34.259 --> 31:37.362 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
activate what our own mechanisms
might be
able to do for us.

31:37.395 --> 31:41.867 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Katie
Couric, from where
you stand, that money, do you
look to Congress?

31:41.900 --> 31:43.735 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I mean, what are we talking
about here?

31:43.769 --> 31:50.208 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATIE COURIC: Well, of course we
need a bigger
-- I think we need more
sustained and funding

31:50.242 --> 31:54.880 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for government and from Congress
and for the
NIH, for the NCI.

31:54.913 --> 32:00.752 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think, to Dr. Brawley's
point, we also
need the private sector
involved. We have

32:00.786 --> 32:06.525 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
raised -- I think close to $360
million has
been pledged to Stand Up to
Cancer through

32:06.558 --> 32:12.230 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
corporate and private and
individual donors.
So, we need to come together as
a country

32:12.264 --> 32:16.735 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and say, you know, this has got
to be where
the end of cancer begins. That's
our motto

32:16.768 --> 32:20.138 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
at Stand Up to Cancer, and
really get everyone
involved.

32:20.172 --> 32:24.376 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And I think, under Vice
President Biden's
leadership, he will be able to
galvanize the

32:24.409 --> 32:30.182 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
community that can be as
political at times,
Judy, as TV news, if you can
imagine that...

32:30.215 --> 32:31.583 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

32:31.616 --> 32:33.919 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATIE COURIC: ... with a lot of
overlapping
and competing interests.

32:33.952 --> 32:38.223 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, we really do need to come
together as
a country, and I think we will
able to accomplish

32:38.256 --> 32:43.295 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
incredible things, and
especially if we have
a more coordinated, sustained
effort.

32:43.328 --> 32:47.165 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, just quickly
from all three
of you, Dr. Brawley first,
what's the message

32:47.199 --> 32:53.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that people out there right now
who either
have cancer or have a loved one
with cancer

32:53.205 --> 32:55.273 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
-- how much hope should they
have right now?

