43:20.631 --> 43:22.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LAURA MILVY, Trouble Finding
Work: I am almost
55.

43:22.733 --> 43:23.501 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA TROGDON, Trouble Finding
Work: I am 58
years old.

43:23.534 --> 43:24.569 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
WOMAN: Fifty-seven.

43:24.602 --> 43:25.970 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DENISE CARRILLO, Trouble Finding
Work: Sixty-four.

43:26.003 --> 43:29.040 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CYNTHIA JOSAYMA, Trouble Finding
Work: I count
myself as 8 plus 50.

43:29.073 --> 43:30.475 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

43:30.508 --> 43:35.880 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: All of these women
have had trouble
finding work since 2008.

43:35.913 --> 43:38.249 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Cynthia Josayma used to work in
international
development.

43:38.282 --> 43:45.456 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CYNTHIA JOSAYMA: When the
recession went into
place, my age community all lost
their jobs.

43:45.490 --> 43:49.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they have found that, in
general, the
middle-age American woman is
marginalized.

43:49.594 --> 43:53.831 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DANA MICHAELS, Trouble Finding
Work: High-tech
firms especially don't want you.

43:53.865 --> 44:00.538 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Former sales rep
Dana Michaels
has been looking for a job for
two years.

44:00.571 --> 44:08.646 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANA MICHAELS: They have a
culture of ping-pong
at the beer Fridays. I applied
for a place

44:08.679 --> 44:09.881 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that had nap Thursdays.

44:09.914 --> 44:11.449 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Nap Thursdays?

44:11.482 --> 44:15.453 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DANA MICHAELS: Yes. And I could
just see myself
putting the blankets over them.

44:15.486 --> 44:19.257 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Now, wait a second.
These young
people were taking naps?

44:19.290 --> 44:24.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANA MICHAELS: On Thursdays. I
was at least
double their age. And I'm sure
they looked

44:24.462 --> 44:26.664 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
at me like, oh, this old lady's
not going
to fit in.

44:26.697 --> 44:33.471 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Though this was
high-tech San
Francisco, the problem extends
nationwide.

44:33.504 --> 44:38.109 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Denise Carrillo has been
unemployed since
losing her fashion industry job
in New York

44:38.142 --> 44:39.877 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
in 2007.

44:39.911 --> 44:45.750 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Did you feel you were being
discriminated
against because you were a
somewhat older

44:45.783 --> 44:47.785 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
woman?

44:47.818 --> 44:52.857 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DENISE CARRILLO: Yes. Yes, I
did. The experience
was there, my confidence was
there. The compliments

44:52.890 --> 44:58.329 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
just rolled. But I was older.
And that's when
I decided, relocate.

44:58.362 --> 45:02.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But when you came
here from New
York two-and-a-half years ago,
did you get

45:02.533 --> 45:05.736 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
responses to the resumes that
you sent out?

45:05.770 --> 45:08.105 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DENISE CARRILLO: No. None. No
responses.

45:08.139 --> 45:13.444 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: The plight of older
women looking
for work was the buzz at last
week's annual

45:13.477 --> 45:18.983 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
meeting of the American Economic
Association,
thanks in part to a Federal
Reserve study

45:19.016 --> 45:26.424 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
making headlines: Women over 50
now account
for half of the long-term
unemployed.

45:26.457 --> 45:30.595 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But does that mean they're being
discriminated
against, more than, say, men
over 50?

45:30.628 --> 45:32.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID NEUMARK, Economist,
University of California,
Irvine: This is, of course, one
of the reasons

45:32.530 --> 45:36.067 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
economists step in, you know,
because we're
always a little -- a little
skeptical of those

45:36.100 --> 45:36.901 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
interpretations.

45:36.934 --> 45:38.736 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Economist David
Neumark.

45:38.769 --> 45:41.472 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID NEUMARK: Because we have
all not gotten
jobs we have applied for, and it
doesn't mean

45:41.505 --> 45:46.143 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we were discriminated against
because of whatever
feature we have, age, race, sex,
whatever

45:46.177 --> 45:47.878 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
it might be.

45:47.912 --> 45:53.384 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But economists can
test these
interpretations with field
experiments, the

45:53.417 --> 45:58.723 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
most famous of which may be the
audit study
summarized in this video, where
thousands

45:58.756 --> 46:05.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of made-up resumes were mailed
to employers,
identical, except for the names,
half black-sounding,

46:05.262 --> 46:07.465 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
half-white.

46:07.498 --> 46:17.274 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The results? Black-sounding
names were 50
percent less likely to get
follow-up calls.

46:17.308 --> 46:24.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
David Neumark used the audit
study approach
to study ageism and sexism. He
sent out resumes

46:24.281 --> 46:30.454 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in 12 cities, using women's
names for thousands
of administrative assistant and
retail sales

46:30.488 --> 46:34.625 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
jobs, men's names for custodian
and security
guard.

46:34.659 --> 46:40.431 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He also varied the age: A third
of the fictional
job hunters were around 30, a
third around

46:40.464 --> 46:48.472 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
50, a final third in their
mid-60s. The results
were dramatically different by
age, but just

46:48.506 --> 46:50.341 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
among the women.

46:50.374 --> 46:53.210 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID NEUMARK: The youngest
group, 30-year-old
or so, get about 15 percent
callback rates,

46:53.244 --> 46:58.783 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
even higher in sales, the
middle-age group
lower, and the oldest group by
far the lowest.

46:58.816 --> 47:03.120 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's a hint that older male
workers have
lower callback rates than
younger male workers,

47:03.154 --> 47:08.159 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but there's much stronger
evidence, in terms
of magnitudes and how robust the
finding is,

47:08.192 --> 47:10.027 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of age discrimination against
older women.

47:10.061 --> 47:13.230 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOANNA LAHEY, Economist: Those
dark red dots
are fixations. That's where the
eye is pausing.

47:13.264 --> 47:19.170 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Economist Joanna
Lahey did a
similar study, sending out 8,000
made-up resumes

47:19.203 --> 47:26.310 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
and an eye-scanning lab
experiment studying
how long H.R. managers looked at
resumes.

47:26.343 --> 47:28.345 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The red dots tell you where and
for how long.

47:28.379 --> 47:31.682 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOANNA LAHEY: And we see the
years on the
employment history, and we see
the education

47:31.716 --> 47:33.451 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and the year that they got their
education.

47:33.484 --> 47:38.589 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: The managers looked
longer at
younger resumes, looked longer
at the items

47:38.622 --> 47:40.291 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
indicating age.

47:40.324 --> 47:42.393 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOANNA LAHEY: This one, for
example, says,
"I'm willing to embrace change,"
which is

47:42.426 --> 47:45.896 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
something that the AARP used to
recommend
that you put on your resume and
then it stopped

47:45.930 --> 47:46.764 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
recommending.

47:46.797 --> 47:48.299 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Because it didn't
work?

47:48.332 --> 47:50.534 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOANNA LAHEY: Well, my first
study found that
it actually hurt older people.

47:50.568 --> 47:56.474 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: Because it
identified them as
card-carrying members of AARP,
Lahey suspects,

47:56.507 --> 47:58.075 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and therefore at least 50.

47:58.109 --> 48:01.312 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, you had people starting in
their mid-30s
all the way to the mid-70s.

48:01.345 --> 48:02.480 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOANNA LAHEY: Yes.

48:02.513 --> 48:05.783 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And when does age
discrimination
start?

48:05.816 --> 48:07.952 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOANNA LAHEY: Immediately. It
starts at age
35.

48:07.985 --> 48:09.754 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: Really?

48:09.787 --> 48:15.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOANNA LAHEY: Yes. It's a pretty
steady process.
As you get older, your amount of
callbacks

48:15.426 --> 48:16.327 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
decrease.

48:16.360 --> 48:18.496 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And it's women more
than men?

48:18.529 --> 48:20.197 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOANNA LAHEY: It's definitely
women more than
men.

48:20.231 --> 48:23.501 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So the evidence is
clear, but
what's the explanation?

48:23.534 --> 48:27.404 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID NEUMARK: The evolutionary
biologists
bring everything back to you
know, reproduction,

48:27.438 --> 48:29.540 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
right? Older men can reproduce.
Older women
can't.

48:29.573 --> 48:32.576 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TINA FEY: And then we put her in
the boat
and we push her out into the
water and we

48:32.610 --> 48:37.181 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
drink champagne to salute how
(EXPLETIVE DELETED)
she was for so many years.
Cheers. Cheers.

48:37.214 --> 48:45.222 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So, it could be
that it's really
something inherent that's passed
on from our

48:45.256 --> 48:51.796 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
evolutionary heritage that just
says, older
women, not so much, older men,
doesn't make

48:51.829 --> 48:53.631 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a difference?

48:53.664 --> 48:56.834 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID NEUMARK: It could be. I
mean, I think
the notion that age signals
something, and

48:56.867 --> 49:01.872 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it's -- for some people at
least, it's a negative,
is not -- is not crazy.

49:01.906 --> 49:05.709 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: No, not crazy, as
even our older
women acknowledged.

49:05.743 --> 49:07.411 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA TROGDON: I'm trying to
think back to

49:07.444 --> 49:09.246 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Lisa Trogdon is 58.

49:09.280 --> 49:15.386 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA TROGDON: ... what I thought
was, when
I was younger. And 50, when I
was 20, 25,

49:15.419 --> 49:22.193 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
seemed old. And as a young
person, I didn't
have the perspective, like I do
now to realize,

49:22.226 --> 49:24.428 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
oh, they have valuable
experience.

49:24.461 --> 49:29.366 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LAURA MILVY: Maybe it's all a
fear, a fear
of older, more experienced
people.

49:29.400 --> 49:33.771 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But what's crazy is
that age
signals something so much more
negative for

49:33.804 --> 49:35.773 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
women than men.

49:35.806 --> 49:37.575 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And says economist Teresa
Ghilarducci:

49:37.608 --> 49:41.278 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TERESA GHILARDUCCI, Economist:
It's going
to be a bigger problem, this age
discrimination

49:41.312 --> 49:47.651 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
problem, for women as more and
more women
are having to work longer,
because of divorce,

49:47.685 --> 49:54.258 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or because they have eroded
pensions, or lower
pensions, because even if they
worked their

49:54.291 --> 49:58.662 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
whole life, they were paid less,
and so they
accumulated less pensions.

49:58.696 --> 50:02.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And as Laura Milvy
asked at the
vocational center:

50:02.399 --> 50:05.836 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LAURA MILVY: If we're all going
to live to
100 years, and you're trying to
make women

50:05.870 --> 50:10.741 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in their 50s stop working, what
are we going
to do for the next 50 years?.

50:10.774 --> 50:12.543 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Good question.

50:12.576 --> 50:19.316 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is "PBS NewsHour" economics
correspondent
Paul Solman, reporting from San
Francisco.

50:19.350 --> 50:32.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And now another
in our Brief
But Spectacular series, where we
ask interesting

50:32.229 --> 50:34.098 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
people about their passions.

50:34.131 --> 50:40.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For six decades, Ken Van Sickle
has been quietly
producing photographs in his
darkroom, located

50:40.537 --> 50:45.609 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the center of Manhattan. His
photos range
from documenting the bohemian
life of New

50:45.643 --> 50:51.348 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
York and Paris in the 1950s and
'60s to pushing
the limits of the medium itself.

50:51.382 --> 50:54.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KEN VAN SICKLE, Photographer: If
you walk
out of the front of the Flatiron
Building

50:54.451 --> 50:57.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and you walk straight across the
street, you
walk right through my door. Then
you have

50:57.655 --> 51:01.358 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to go 91 steps up the stairs,
which is really
good for me, because it keeps me
healthy.

51:01.392 --> 51:07.197 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm 83 years old now. I moved
into this building
in 1963. And it's
rent-controlled. And it's

51:07.231 --> 51:12.136 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a landmark building, and I'm a
senior citizen.
So, I don't pay much rent.
That's the only

51:12.169 --> 51:19.710 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
reason I can live here at all.

51:19.743 --> 51:24.682 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't have a favorite place to
take photographs
or even a favorite subject. I
carry a camera.

51:24.715 --> 51:27.751 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If I go out into the hallway, I
carry a camera
with me.

51:27.785 --> 51:33.824 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When I was in Paris, I was 23, I
think, and
I wanted to shoot everything I
saw, but I

51:33.857 --> 51:37.594 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
didn't have enough money to buy,
like, more
than like a roll of film every
two weeks.

51:37.628 --> 51:41.365 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And somebody said that Chet
Baker was playing
over at the American club. And I
went over

51:41.398 --> 51:47.404 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and I took two pictures, and one
of them is
out of focus, and the other one
is a great

51:47.438 --> 51:49.239 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
photo.

51:49.273 --> 51:52.076 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I'm not a concerned
photographer. I'm not
trying to prove anything in any
way politically

51:52.109 --> 51:57.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or otherwise. I'm interested in
beauty and
sort of the subtle moments of
everyday life.

51:57.848 --> 52:02.219 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This picture was called "The
Regular." The
chairs in the foreground are
overlapping,

52:02.252 --> 52:07.992 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
overlapping planes in parallel
recession.
This picture, I just call it
"Washington Square."

52:08.025 --> 52:13.097 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Laboratories tend to print it
light, but it
should be dark like this.

52:13.130 --> 52:16.300 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Grand Central Station, I don't
know why there
was only one person walking in
there. I had

52:16.333 --> 52:22.906 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
just gotten off the train. I
call this "Firemen."
The arch had caved in on five
firemen. The

52:22.940 --> 52:26.243 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Metropolitan Museum chose this
to be in the
permanent collection.

52:26.276 --> 52:31.415 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are a lot of things that
make a good
photograph. You have to think
about texture

52:31.448 --> 52:35.886 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and gesture and composition, and
all the things
that painting has in it.
Technology doesn't

52:35.919 --> 52:41.025 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
change the way photography is.
It just -- it
makes it available to more
people, which means

52:41.058 --> 52:45.462 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there's going to be much, much
more really
terrible pictures taken or
pictures that are

52:45.496 --> 52:49.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
totally dependent on subject,
which is all,
all right.

52:49.600 --> 52:53.003 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you were there when the
Hindenburg caught
on fire, and you took a picture
of it, that's

52:53.037 --> 52:56.907 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a great photograph. But you're
not a great
photographer, because you can't
repeat that

52:56.940 --> 52:58.776 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in everyday things.

52:58.809 --> 53:05.582 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What a great photographer does
is, they are
consistently able to make
something in a style

53:05.616 --> 53:11.255 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that's personal to themselves.
My pictures
don't depend on extreme
sharpness. They depend

53:11.288 --> 53:15.259 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on the composition and on the
subject and
on the way I see it.

53:15.292 --> 53:21.465 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My name is Ken Van Sickle. This
is my Brief
But Spectacular take on sharing
what I see.

53:21.498 --> 53:27.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And you can see
more of our
Brief But Spectacular series on
